00:33:49.387 --> 00:33:51.720
This just sort of makes it
easier, a not to scale graph.

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:55.330
Let's say we give someone-- we
say to them, look, you're poor.

00:33:55.330 --> 00:33:57.950
We're going to give
you $500 in cash.

00:33:57.950 --> 00:34:00.130
Well, now all we've done
is shift out your budget

00:34:00.130 --> 00:34:03.007
constraint from 5,000 to 5,500.

00:34:03.007 --> 00:34:04.840
OK, we've shifted out
your budget constraint

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:07.570
from 5,000 to 5,500.

00:34:07.570 --> 00:34:09.460
What does that do
to your choices?

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:12.380
Well, consider two
different types of people.

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:17.840
Person y, OK, they used to
be on indifference curve I0.

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:20.447
They used to spend almost
all their income on food

00:34:20.447 --> 00:34:21.489
and not a lot on shelter.

00:34:21.489 --> 00:34:23.659
They were probably homeless, OK?

00:34:23.659 --> 00:34:25.460
So they spent all
their money on food

00:34:25.460 --> 00:34:27.080
and were basically homeless.

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:28.112
Now what do they do?

00:34:28.112 --> 00:34:30.320
Well, they spend a little
