only spent $300 on food.

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:33.270
So we are forcing them to not
be on their preferred budget

00:38:33.270 --> 00:38:34.740
constraint.

00:38:34.740 --> 00:38:40.420
Rather, we're forcing
them down to point x2,

00:38:40.420 --> 00:38:43.420
which is they'll spend the
minimum they can on food,

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:47.670
but the minimum is $500, OK?

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:50.470
We are forcing them
down to point x2.

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:52.420
Now why do I say forcing them?

00:38:52.420 --> 00:38:55.600
Why do I know for sure they
are being forced, that they're

00:38:55.600 --> 00:38:59.260
less happy at x2 than they would
have been when they gave them

00:38:59.260 --> 00:38:59.763
the cash?

00:38:59.763 --> 00:39:00.930
How do I know that for sure?

00:39:00.930 --> 00:39:01.930
Yeah?

00:39:01.930 --> 00:39:03.930
AUDIENCE: They're at a
lower indifference curve.

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:05.170
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:39:05.170 --> 00:39:06.295
Think of it this way.

00:39:06.295 --> 00:39:08.170
The fundamental-- one
of the important things

00:39:08.170 --> 00:39:09.850
is people always get
to the point that

00:39:09.850 --> 00:39:11.798
makes them happiest, OK?

00:39:11.798 --> 00:39:13.840
We call it the robustness
of economic equilibria.

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:15.882
People get to the point
that makes them happiest.

00:39:15.882 --> 00:39:19.050
They want-- they
always before had

00:39:19.050 --> 00:39:22.175
the choice of spending $500 on
food, and they chose not to.

00:39:22.175 --> 00:39:24.300
Therefore, if you force
them to spend $500 on food,

00:39:24.300 --> 00:39:26.915
they must be less happy, OK?

00:39:26.915 --> 00:39:27.790
Think of it that way.

00:39:27.790 --> 00:39:29.680
They always could have
spent $500 on food.

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:30.460
They didn't.

00:39:30.460 --> 00:39:31.877
Therefore, in
forcing them, you're

00:39:31.877 --> 00:39:34.220
making them less happy, OK?

00:39:34.220 --> 00:39:38.150
So they are worse off, OK?

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:39.500
They are forced to spend.

00:39:39.500 --> 00:39:41.090
They'd rather spend
some of that money

00:39:41.090 --> 00:39:43.970
and find a nicer place to live,
but we're not letting them.

00:39:43.970 --> 00:39:47.300
We're making them buy food, OK?

00:39:47.300 --> 00:39:48.870
Do people-- I don't want--

00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:52.200
I just want to know if people
understand the graphics here

00:39:52.200 --> 00:39:53.870
and the conclusions I drew.

00:39:53.870 --> 00:39:56.770
OK, now why?

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:58.130
Why are we doing this?

00:39:58.130 --> 00:40:00.610
Why would you-- they're
better off with cash.

00:40:00.610 --> 00:40:02.860
Why would we force
them to have food?

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:04.760
Yeah?

00:40:04.760 --> 00:40:06.660
AUDIENCE: Say
because what makes--

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:08.550
what puts people on the
highest indifference

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:10.660
is just what makes them
happiest, but not necessarily

00:40:10.660 --> 00:40:12.202
what makes them like
live the longest

00:40:12.202 --> 00:40:14.050
or like have the best
health So, perhaps,

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:16.800
like if you never spend money
on food, and then you die,

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:17.998
that would be really bad.

00:40:17.998 --> 00:40:20.290
JONATHAN GRUBER: OK, but,
basically, what you're saying

00:40:20.290 --> 00:40:22.940
is you know better than the guy.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:24.190
Let me-- I'm not accusing you.

00:40:24.190 --> 00:40:28.320
I'm just saying, look,
if people knew best,

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:33.420
maybe they'd like to just like
have a nice house and die, OK?

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:35.820
If people knew
best, then there'd

00:40:35.820 --> 00:40:38.080
be no reason to do this.

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:41.210
The reason to do this is because
we think they don't know best.

00:40:41.210 --> 00:40:44.110
So, for example, let's change
the label on the y-axis, just

00:40:44.110 --> 00:40:44.750
a small change.

00:40:44.750 --> 00:40:47.091
Let's cross out shelter
and write cocaine.

00:40:47.091 --> 00:40:49.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:49.860 --> 00:40:50.850
OK?

00:40:50.850 --> 00:40:53.640
Well, in that case, maybe
we don't feel so bad

00:40:53.640 --> 00:40:57.590
about forcing the guy to buy
food instead of cocaine, OK?

00:40:57.590 --> 00:41:00.290
In other words, this a
program which might make

00:41:00.290 --> 00:41:03.380
sense if we are paternalistic.

00:41:03.380 --> 00:41:07.010
Now we're getting into normative
economics, paternalistic.

00:41:07.010 --> 00:41:09.110
If we think that people
won't necessarily

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:12.350
make the right decisions
for themselves,

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:14.600
then it may be worth
actually making them

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:17.100
worse off because
they're not worse off.

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:19.370
Their perceived
benefits are worse,

00:41:19.370 --> 00:41:23.070
but they don't know
what they're doing, OK?

00:41:23.070 --> 00:41:25.643
Now you can see why--

00:41:25.643 --> 00:41:27.060
I hope you can
sort of immediately

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:31.230
see why this concept makes
economists a little nervous

00:41:31.230 --> 00:41:34.213
because why do we know what they
want better than they do, OK?

00:41:34.213 --> 00:41:35.880
So it makes people a
little bit nervous,

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:37.630
economists a little
bit nervous, and a lot

00:41:37.630 --> 00:41:40.320
of people a little bit nervous
to say, gee, maybe they're

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:42.254
just happier doing cocaine.

00:41:42.254 --> 00:41:44.462
And how do we know that
that's the wrong way for them

00:41:44.462 --> 00:41:45.504
to spend their resources?

00:41:45.504 --> 00:41:46.025
Yeah?

00:41:46.025 --> 00:41:46.873
AUDIENCE: Well,
like can't you look

00:41:46.873 --> 00:41:49.330
at it from the perspective of
like this is taxpayer money,

00:41:49.330 --> 00:41:49.830
right?

00:41:49.830 --> 00:41:51.562
So then aren't you
also just factoring

00:41:51.562 --> 00:41:54.320
in how the taxpayer wants to
spend their money and then

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:56.760
their indifference curve
and all their information?

00:41:56.760 --> 00:41:57.740
JONATHAN GRUBER: That's
a very good point.

00:41:57.740 --> 00:41:59.448
Now but there's sort
of two points there.

00:41:59.448 --> 00:42:04.650
First of all, if the taxpayers'
