00:44:49.690 --> 00:44:51.410
Are they making a difference?

00:44:51.410 --> 00:44:54.850
Well, actually, we've run
an experiment on this, OK?

00:44:54.850 --> 00:44:57.070
We're going to talk
in this class a lot

00:44:57.070 --> 00:45:00.430
about empirical
results in economics.

00:45:00.430 --> 00:45:04.000
This class is mostly going
to be a theoretical class.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.550
That is we'll talk
about models and ideas.

00:45:06.550 --> 00:45:08.632
But we're also--
since, basically, I'm

00:45:08.632 --> 00:45:10.090
an empirical
economist, we're going

00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:13.990
to talk about empirical
economics, which is results

00:45:13.990 --> 00:45:15.938
and testing the
theories we develop.

00:45:15.938 --> 00:45:17.730
Empirical economics,
here's a great example

00:45:17.730 --> 00:45:20.890
of empirical economics is we
set up a theoretical model.

00:45:20.890 --> 00:45:22.720
You always want to
start with the theory,

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:24.550
but the theory sometimes
has predictions,

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:25.390
which are uncertain.

00:45:25.390 --> 00:45:27.640
Here we have an uncertain
prediction from theory about

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:29.890
whether food stamps will
affect food purchases or not.

00:45:29.890 --> 00:45:31.150
So let's test it.

00:45:31.150 --> 00:45:33.210
And the way we test
it is we actually

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:37.175
have run food stamps cash out
experiments where we literally

00:45:37.175 --> 00:45:39.300
take guys on food stamps
and give them cash instead

00:45:39.300 --> 00:45:42.330
and watch what happens to their
consumption before and after.

00:45:42.330 --> 00:45:44.350
It's a real randomized trial.

00:45:44.350 --> 00:45:46.050
We literally flip a coin.

00:45:46.050 --> 00:45:47.700
Heads, you keep
your food stamps.

00:45:47.700 --> 00:45:49.290
Tails, we replace
those food stamps

00:45:49.290 --> 00:45:50.610
with an equal amount of cash.

00:45:50.610 --> 00:45:53.010
Then we watch what happens.

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:59.450
What happens is that people
spend about 15% less on food

00:45:59.450 --> 00:46:01.430
when you give them cash
instead of food stamps.

00:46:01.430 --> 00:46:05.090
That is food stamps is forcing
people to spend about 15%

00:46:05.090 --> 00:46:06.560
more on food than
they would like

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:08.470
to unconstrained by the cash.

00:46:08.470 --> 00:46:08.970
Yeah?

00:46:08.970 --> 00:46:11.505
AUDIENCE: Yeah, this gets
you into the behavior of

00:46:11.505 --> 00:46:12.200
[INAUDIBLE].

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:14.510
I remember reading an
experiment like, if you

00:46:14.510 --> 00:46:17.230
have the price of gas go down,
the actual like amount of money

00:46:17.230 --> 00:46:19.895
spent on gas is constant.

00:46:19.895 --> 00:46:21.520
And this might
translate to food stamps

00:46:21.520 --> 00:46:24.000
because like food stamps
are like explicitly on food.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.375
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yeah, you
know, that's a great question.

00:46:26.375 --> 00:46:29.028
And that's you're asking about
richer theory, richer theory.

00:46:29.028 --> 00:46:30.945
And I'm telling you that
I'm going to give you

00:46:30.945 --> 00:46:31.640
the empirical evidence.

00:46:31.640 --> 00:46:33.080
So, whatever the theory
is, the empirical evidence

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:33.840
tells you what happens.

00:46:33.840 --> 00:46:35.810
And there's different
explanations for why.

00:46:35.810 --> 00:46:39.590
So the empirical evidence is
that, basically, the price

00:46:39.590 --> 00:46:43.200
of our paternalism is 15%, OK?

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:45.480
We are making people,
effectively, 15% worse off.

00:46:45.480 --> 00:46:48.760
We're making them spend 15%
more food than they want to.

00:46:48.760 --> 00:46:50.500
So is it worth it?

00:46:50.500 --> 00:46:53.047
Well, actually, the
evidence is starting

00:46:53.047 --> 00:46:55.380
to pour in that it might not
be worth it because there's

00:46:55.380 --> 00:46:57.338
starting to be a lot of
experiments where we're

00:46:57.338 --> 00:46:59.940
giving people just cash,
especially in developing

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:00.922
countries.

00:47:00.922 --> 00:47:02.380
In developing
countries, the answer

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:03.960
seems to be just
giving people cash

00:47:03.960 --> 00:47:06.260
makes them better
off, that actually,

00:47:06.260 --> 00:47:07.860
especially in
developing countries,

00:47:07.860 --> 00:47:10.410
people use the cash
in productive ways.

00:47:10.410 --> 00:47:14.643
So, for example, they have a
series of evaluation programs

00:47:14.643 --> 00:47:17.310
where they've given people cash,
mostly in developing countries,

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:20.728
in Africa in particular,
some in the US.

00:47:20.728 --> 00:47:22.770
And they find that people
spend relatively little

00:47:22.770 --> 00:47:26.130
of that on drugs and
alcohol, but they actually

00:47:26.130 --> 00:47:27.707
tend to spend it productively.

00:47:27.707 --> 00:47:29.790
And, in fact, they found,
in developing countries,

00:47:29.790 --> 00:47:32.070
this often provides valuable
resources for individuals

00:47:32.070 --> 00:47:33.250
to start businesses.

00:47:33.250 --> 00:47:36.690
So they ran experiment Uganda
where a nonprofit company

00:47:36.690 --> 00:47:38.610
randomly offered
a group of women

00:47:38.610 --> 00:47:43.440
$150, which is huge
relative to their income.

00:47:43.440 --> 00:47:48.660
That's 50% to 100% of annual
income in Uganda, $150.

00:47:48.660 --> 00:47:53.010
And what they found was, after
two months-- after 18 months,

00:47:53.010 --> 00:47:55.560
these women had used that
money to start businesses.

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:57.480
And that actually
raised their earnings.

00:47:57.480 --> 00:48:00.720
That actually effectively
doubled their earnings.

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:05.220
From that one
injection of cash, it

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:08.790
led them to actually double
their annual earnings, OK?

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:10.890
So that leads one to
think that maybe we

00:48:10.890 --> 00:48:13.660
should stop being paternalistic
and just give cash.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:16.320
Unfortunately, if you're a
reader of policy websites like

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.320
I am, the best one
of which is vox.com--

00:48:18.320 --> 00:48:19.535
it's a great website--

00:48:19.535 --> 00:48:21.660
they had an article just
the other day pointing out

00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:24.118
how they actually followed
these women up nine years later.

00:48:24.118 --> 00:48:26.500
And, nine years later, the
effect had totally gone away.

00:48:26.500 --> 00:48:29.940
So the story isn't quite
necessarily positive,

00:48:29.940 --> 00:48:31.020
but it's not negative.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:32.700
They're not worse
off, but it looks

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:34.200
like, at least what
in the short run

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:36.990
made them better off, well,
that effect fades over time.

00:48:36.990 --> 00:48:38.610
But the bottom line
is, at this point,

00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:39.750
I think the evidence
is sort of probably

00:48:39.750 --> 00:48:41.700
in favor of being
less paternalistic

00:48:41.700 --> 00:48:45.090
and just giving
people cash, but that

00:48:45.090 --> 00:48:47.670
runs into a lot of difficulties
in terms of our concerns

00:48:47.670 --> 00:48:49.350
about how people will spend it.

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:51.150
So let me stop there.

